  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations to prevent, detect, and report money laundering activities. These typically include:\n\n1. Know Your Customer (KYC) requirements\n- Verify customer identities\n- Conduct background checks\n- Assess customer risk profiles\n\n2. Suspicious Activity Reporting (SAR)\n- Identify and report potentially suspicious transactions\n- File reports with relevant authorities\n- Maintain detailed transaction records\n\n3. Anti-Money Laundering (AML) compliance programs\n- Implement internal policies and procedures\n- Train employees on detection and reporting\n- Conduct regular risk assessments\n\n4. Transaction monitoring\n- Track unusual financial activities\n- Flag potentially suspicious transactions\n- Maintain audit trails\n\n5. Due diligence requirements\n- Perform enhanced screening for high-risk customers\n- Verify source of funds\n- Maintain ongoing monitoring\n\n6. Regulatory compliance\n- Follow laws like Bank Secrecy Act\n- Adhere to international standards\n- Cooperate with law enforcement investigations\n\nFinancial institutions can face significant legal penalties, including substantial fines and potential criminal charges, for failing to meet these obligations.",
